{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:56:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1221"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1221"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.03,0.69,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1221"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"672"},{"type":"tags","id":"1407"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28470"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old building worker presents to the General Practice clinic with a painful toe (Image). This has been giving him trouble for the last ten days, and he has not been able to wear his work boots. His general practitioner has prescribed antibiotics, and he has been using topical antiseptics. This is the fourth time in the last two years that he has had this problem.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Change the course of antibiotics","Silver nitrate cauterisation","Alginate dressings","Wedge resection of the toenail","Resection and complete nail bed ablation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a paronychia. The reason for its persistence and recurrence is an ingrown toenail. Ingrown toenail problems are usually the result of excessive or incorrect trimming of the outer margins of the nail plate. Repetitive trauma such as tight footwear or running may also lead to nail damage. The skin tissues adjacent to the damaged nail become infected, often with a spike of nail growing under the skin fold. Until that problem is dealt with, the infection will persist and recur. The most effective treatment is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ewedge resection of the toenail\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically of the lateral (ingrown) section of the nail (including that portion of the nail bed) and the adjacent infected tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA complete nail bed resection\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary, as the problem relates to the outer borders only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this is a foreign body reaction, \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eantiseptics\u003C/strong\u003E will not reduce infection rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilver nitrate cautery\u003C/strong\u003E does not have a role in management. Application of a gutter splint is a non-surgical option of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Recurrent paronychia frequently require local nail bed resection.","Ingrown toenails can lead to persistent paronychia if not properly managed."],"references":["Mayeaux EJ Jr, Carter C, Murphy TE. Ingrown Toenail Management. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Aug 1;100(3):158-164. PMID: 31361106. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31361106/","Hassan RE, Khan L, Shah SH, Naeem H, Noor N, Iqbal M, Dawood Khan F, Rehman Z, Ahmad W, Tanveer S, Khan AU, Shah SH. Surgical Strategies for Ingrown Toenails: A Comprehensive Review of Techniques, Outcomes, and Advancements. Cureus. 2024 Jan 18;16(1):e52501. doi: 10.7759/cureus.52501. PMID: 38371148; PMCID: PMC10874229. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10874229/","Exley V, Jones K, O\u0027Carroll G, Watson J, Backhouse M. A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomised controlled trials on surgical treatments for ingrown toenails part I: recurrence and relief of symptoms. J Foot Ankle Res. 2023 Jun 10;16(1):35. doi: 10.1186/s13047-023-00631-1. PMID: 37301845; PMCID: PMC10257290. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37301845/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1221"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20192"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20192"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36018434-71f1-4d91-972e-a4ec537e3cdb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/36018434-71f1-4d91-972e-a4ec537e3cdb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T15:09:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T15:10:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1221"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-